<TITLE> SEC slaps restriction on GP share trade </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 CORRECTION: SEC move effective from Feb 10 Dhaka, Feb 9 (bdnews24.com)  Investors will no longer be able to buy into Grameenphone with immature funds as the market regulator has suspended netting facilities for shares of the market mover until further notice. In a bid to prevent overheating of the bourse, the Securities and Exchange Commission issued a circular Monday announcing the measure, effective Wednesday (Feb 10). "This means no person shall be allowed to buy share of Grameenphone Ltd. against value of sale of other securities (i.e. by using Fund in Transit) within the existing settlement and clearance period," the SEC said. Investors will have to wait for the full clearance period for funds to mature, which is three days after the day of trade, before buying into GPor pay in cash. GP, Bangladesh's largest mobile operator, gained for the sixth consecutive day on Monday. It rose 6.15 per cent or Tk 16 to close at Tk 310.60, topping the turnover board with shares worth Tk 1.63 billion changing hands. The country's first and lone listed telecom company debuted on the bourse in November as Bangladesh's largest ever issue, which continues to impact market capitalisation as its share price goes up or down
